  <a name="comment-1418"></a>
  <img alt="Avatar" class="gravatar" src="http://www.gravatar.com/avatar.php?gravatar_id=d41d8cd98f00b204e9800998ecf8427e&amp;size=60" />
  <cite><strong>itchy</strong> </cite> said 1 day later:<br />
  <p>At this point, DHH has become like Alan Greenspan. Everything he says gets amplified.</p>


	<p>Since all credit and blame for every aspect of what Rails does and should do gets funneled to him, I&#8217;m betting this was the 10th &#8220;Rails can&#8217;t do X&#8221; he had heard that day.</p>


	<p>I cut him a lot of slack. Yes, he&#8217;s &#8216;opinionated,&#8217; as he&#8217;s often said himself. I&#8217;ve never met him, but he seems pleasant enough in general. Nevertheless, I&#8217;m sure he has bad days.</p>


	<p>When someone says &#8220;Rails can&#8217;t do X,&#8221; no, they&#8217;re not necessarily blaming Rails, but sometimes they are. &#8220;Rails can&#8217;t do X&#8221; is frequently an abbreviation of: &#8220;Rails can&#8217;t do X, so Rails is useless.&#8221;</p>


	<p>So I can see where DHH got defensive: Here&#8217;s a company doing bleeding-edge stuff, choosing to use a framework for it, then saying the framework doesn&#8217;t have the stuff out-of-the-box to handle the requests.</p>


	<p>I agree, it looks like the Twitter guys didn&#8217;t mean it as a criticism, but I can see easily where DHH would see it as such.</p>


	<p>Maybe he should be more measured with his responses, but, hey, so should many people.</p>
